**Competitor content approach:** Most top-ranking pink nail pages are pure gallery round-ups — 26 to 66 images with minimal editorial depth. They list looks without telling the reader which shade belongs to which season, which finish suits which occasion, or how to navigate the enormous shade spectrum intelligently. Skin tone guidance is usually surface-level or absent entirely. Seasonal structure is rare; most pages dump all shades together with no seasonal logic.

**Visual patterns:** Competitors carry 12–20 images for mid-range pink posts; top-performing gallery posts run 26–66 images. For our all-year inspirational intent with 4 seasonal subsections, 14–18 well-curated images with editorial captions is the right density — quality over quantity wins against pure gallery pages.

**Recommended image count:** 14–18 images — lead with one hero spring image, 3–4 per season subsection, plus 1–2 for shade spectrum / skin tone section.

### Competitor Gaps

**Questions competitors are NOT answering:**
- Which specific pink sub-shade is actually trending in each season of 2026, and why?
- How does finish (matte, glossy, cat-eye, jelly) transform the same pink shade across seasons?
- What is the difference between blush, baby pink, rose milk, and sheer pink — and when do you wear each?
- Which pink shades photograph best on video calls vs in-person occasions?
- How do you wear pink nails when you're not a "pink person" — the muted mauve and dusty rose angle?
- What does the Barbiecore era mean for hot pink in 2026 — is it still relevant or has it evolved?
- How do you match a specific pink shade to your undertone without a guide full of jargon?

**Missing semantic territory:**
- Dusty mauve as 2026's sophisticated pink
